:::summary
Faith is the foundational principle of action in all religious life — a confident trust in God and in His promises that moves people to act before they have perfect knowledge. The scriptures define faith not as blind credulity but as a well-founded hope in things not yet seen, based on evidence, covenant promises, and the witness of the Holy Ghost. In Latter-day Saint theology, faith in Jesus Christ is the first principle of the gospel and the foundation of salvation.
:::

